    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Your sourdough starter is not dead; it just needs more time to catch up with the feeding. The 68 degrees temperature in your kitchen is a good environment for it. It's possible that your starter has a bit of a slow start, but usually, it will show signs of activity within a day or two after feeding. Just give it a little more time, and don't worry. It could be that the all-purpose flour isn't providing enough nutrients for the yeast to thrive. You might want to try adding some whole grain flour or a little bit of water to your next feed to boost its growth. If you don't see any bubbles or a change in consistency within the next 24 hours, you might consider starting a new starter with fresh flour and water. But don't give up on your current one yet! It could just be taking a little longer to wake up.",
